title: For Sale:  Rampro
postcontent: Up for sale is a Rampro center grip 7mm JI. It was custom built John Illum. Rampro actions are chrome-moly steel. Commonly you'd see them blued, but I had him put a brushed nickel finish on the action and rings. From a few feet away it looks like stainless. The trigger is Illum's own design set at 8 ounces, and there's no creep that I can detect. The action has Remington barrel threads and will accept Remington type triggers. One neat thing is that the action was milled with an integral recoil lug (much like the current Surgeon Action). And the bolt is milled all in one piece-no soldered-on handles and is a 7mm whisper.You'll also note how slick and streamlined the scope rings are. Illum made those as well. His rings mount to the action via two screws from the inside of the ring, a very elegant set-up for sure. Has Bomar sights and Scope rings. Comes with dies and 100 rounds of brass.

postcontent:
Taurus 24/7 OSS Tactical in .40 5.25in barrel 15+1
Don't let the brand fool you. The 24/7 Tactical was developed to compete for a military contract against all the top names in gun making. This model was in the finals when the military canceled the contract. This model is no longer made and has been replaced with the G2 model with only a 4in barrel. This is a great weapon with several unique features. 5.25in barrel, DA/SA mode yet a Striker Fire system. Decocker/Safety and the ability to cycle the trigger repeatedly without racking the slide. Very unique for a striker fire system. Allows you to attempt firing again after a misfire. Easy take down, everything is similar to a Beretta and 1911 rolled into one with the plus of a striker fire system. 24/7 are becoming very sought after weapons. I have one in .45 and .40 that I will probably never sell. I got this one in a trade. I originally thought I would collect and hang on to this but decided not to keep the money tied up. postcontent:
I need to sell to finance another purchase.  The lower is Bushmaster.  I think the upper is another brand. It has C MB stamped on the carry handle just in front of the dials.  It has a collapsible stock and forward assist.  I purchased it used from a dealer in 2008/2009 and I have only put around 25 rounds through it.  It shoots very well and I was surprised with the accuracy at 100 and 200 yards using only the iron sights.  This rifle has a fixed carry handle.  If you want to change out to a flattop rifle, you can buy a stripped flattop upper receiver (around $70) and switch it out to a flattop.  Or keep it with the fixed carry handle.  You can mount optics on top of the carry handle.  Some people may like the optic sitting higher on the rifle so they do not have to lower their head as much to look through optics.

The barrel is 16 inches. It has "C MP 5.56 NATO 1/9 HBAR stamped on it"  One source I found online said this means "Colt Magnafluxed, in 5.56 NATO, 1 in 9 twist, with a HBAR profile" In other words it is a Colt NATO 5.56 chambered barrel that's been MP (Magnetic Particle Tested).  The 1/9 is the twist rate.  The HBAR is a heavy barrel. 

Please email if interested.  I am absolutely firm at $525.  $525 is the price in Raleigh.  I will not drive much more than a few miles to meet at this price.  I am normally over the top accommodating, but at this price, I am not driving very far.  What is pictured is what is included - the rifle and 1 -30 round mag. Steve

title: For Sale/Trade:  S&W Model 10 Snubnose NO DASH Early 1960's Detective Revolver
location: Southern Overland Park, KS 66062, Kansas City, Kansas
postcontent:
I have an early 1960's Smith and Wesson model 10 'no dash' snubnose.
The original detective's sidearm!

'No dash' refers to the fact that this is the first generation of the model 10, as later generations were designated with a dash and a number. I.E model 10-3, model 10-7.
These early models are very desirable, since they often have features that later models do not. Such as the pinned barrel.

They're also quiet collectible, especially these old snubnose revolvers! Hard to find.

This came from a detective in Topeka, sadly the paperwork never showed up after I bought it.

.38 special, I wouldn't shoot modem +P loads in it too often, but it feeds target ammo like a champ.
Springs are all still nice and strong, locks up tight.
The bore looks good to me.

It has some holster wear, there's a spot on the S&W logo that looks like the finish was removed? and  the grips are a bit nicked up. It's certainly not perfect but not abused. I don't think it was shot much.

Overall, looks used but a very solid gun.

Comes with an old leather inside the waistband holster, I don't know if it's period or not, but it definitely has age. It's practically formed to the revolver now.

I looked on gunbroker and similar ones seem to go for around $450, those all have dashes. I haven't found a good comparable one.

Cash or trades, I can trade for just about anything.
Gold, silver, jewelry, bullion, coins, antiques, collectibles, old clocks and watches...

TEXT REDACTED

title: For Sale:  JC Higgins Pump Model 20-12 GA Sears, Roebuck And Co
postcontent:
From 1908 until 1962, Sears, Roebuck & Company sold a wide variety of sporting goods and recreational equipment, including bicycles, golf clubs, rifles, shotguns, and revolvers under the brand name "J. C. Higgins." These products were well made and were popular with the company's historical core of rural and working-class consumers.
Like many other Sears products, the Sears firearms were originally made by major firearm manufacturers. The Model 20 was produced by High Standard Arms, as was the Model 88 revolver.
The J.C. Higgins brand for Sears sporting goods was replaced with the Ted Williams brand. Many of the more durable J.C. Higgins products are still available as second hand items.
The brand name, J. C. Higgins, was based on a real person, John Higgins who was a Sears employee. He moved from his birth country of Ireland to the United States in his late teens and began working for Sears in 1898. He spent his entire working career with Sears and was Vice President for the company for a period of time. He was actually born with no middle name but the Sears Co. presented the idea of labeling their sporting good line with his name and saw it more presentable labeling the brand as J.C. Higgins. He worked with the company until his retirement as head bookkeeper in 1930. Higgins died in 1950. His expertise in sporting goods or sports is unknown. Must be a Missouri resident and have a valid ID.

title: For Sale:  Glock 26 GEN 4. Perfect, has the hard to find "teflon-like" finish+extras.
postcontent:
Perfect gun. This Gen 4 26 has that "teflon" finish that alot of the gen 3's had. Very few of the 4's were lucky enough to get it. Do a search on google. Almost all gen 4's have a smooth, matte black finish. Problem is, that finish shows handling and holster marks the second you use it. Gen 4's come with a third magazine, stippling, larger ambidexterous mag ejector and interchangeable backstraps. The 26 Gen 4's have 3 total backstraps.

This finish looks shinier and even feels extremely indestructable. Just like the tefflon coating on really expensive pans. This gun is perfect. Not so much as a little mark on the barrel ramp (pic 2). I wish I could do a better job of explaining the look/feel of the finish other than it is much more attractive and after watching the youtube videos and reading everything people had to say about it on the Glock forums, compared to the flat matte finish which shows holster wear after each use, this one will take a beating and still look new. 

Some will say, "a Glock is tool and I like it to look used..." Well, my truck is too and I don't want it scratched up/faded after using it when it could look perfect for a long time. Just my opinion.

Has grip extenions for all 3 mags, slide release extension and glock tool along with all the stuff/papers/lock/backstraps, etc. that it came with.

Also has a very nice ankle holster for concealed carry. Can email pics of it.

Email for more pics/info. or text 515 six six 4 5nine78. Thanks.
